<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="62" type="collection and habitat data">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="62">Collection and habitat data.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="62">
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell, JM" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada" pageId="21" pageNumber="76" pagination="1 - 137" title="A revision of the genus Tachinus (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae) of North and Central America." url="10.4039/entm10590fv" volume="90" year="1973">Campbell (1973</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell, JM" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="21" pageNumber="76" pagination="231 - 295" title="New species and records of North American Tachinus Gravenhorst (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae)." url="10.4039/Ent120231-3" volume="120" year="1988">1988</bibRefCitation>
) reported that most specimens of this northern transcontinental species were collected from under animal dung or decaying mushrooms. Adults were also collected from the mouth of animal burrows, in leaf litter and other kinds of decaying organic matter. In Alberta, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tachinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tachinus frigidus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frigidus">Tachinus frigidus</taxonomicName>
was considered to be a mature forest (conifer-dominated) specialist (
<bibRefCitation author="Pohl, GR" journalOrPublisher="Biological Conservation" pageId="21" pageNumber="76" pagination="294 - 307" title="Rove beetles and ground beetles (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Carabidae) as indicators of harvest and regeneration practices in western Canadian foothills forests." url="10.1016/j.biocon.2007.02.011" volume="137" year="2007">Pohl et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
. The only specimen from New Brunswick was collected from a decaying fleshy mushroom during September in a mature, coastal red spruce forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="62" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="62">Distribution in Canada and Alaska.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="62">
AK, YT, NT, BC, AB, MB, ON, QC, NB, NS, LB (
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell, JM" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada" pageId="21" pageNumber="76" pagination="1 - 137" title="A revision of the genus Tachinus (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae) of North and Central America." url="10.4039/entm10590fv" volume="90" year="1973">Campbell 1973</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tachinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tachinus frigidus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frigidus">Tachinus frigidus</taxonomicName>
was listed as occurring in New Brunswick by 
<bibRefCitation author="Majka, CG" journalOrPublisher="Empty Mirrors Press, Halifax, Nova Scotia" pageId="21" pageNumber="76" title="Checklist of the beetles of Maine, USA" url="10.4039/n06-099" year="2011">Majka et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
without any supporting references or data. Here we provide the first documented records from New Brunswick.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
